derivation.yuyuan_name: late 16th cent.: from French immodeste or Latin immodestus, from in- 'not' + modestus (see modest)

entry.def: If you describe someone's behaviour as immodest, you mean that it shocks or embarrasses you because you think that it is rude.

entry.tran: 自吹自擂的;自我吹嘘的;大言不惭的
entry.def: If you say that someone is immodest, you disapprove of the way in which they often say how good, important, or clever they are.

example.ex: He could become ungraciously immodest about his own capacities.
example.tran: 谈及自己的能力,他会自吹自擂大言不惭。

means.word_mean: 1. having or showing an exaggerated opinion of your importance, ability, etc;
2. offending against sexual mores in conduct or appearance
